          "body": "Verse 7 is one of the most important statements of prophetic theology in the entire Old Testament: 'Surely the Lord God does nothing unless He reveals His secret counsel to His servants the prophets.' The word *sod* — the divine council, the intimate deliberative circle — refers to God's inner-circle plans (cf. Jeremiah 23:18, 22; Psalm 25:14). The prophets are not guessing or extrapolating; they have been admitted to the divine council chamber and heard the decree. This verse does two things simultaneously. First, it grounds Amos's ministry: his announcement of judgment is not personal opinion or political commentary — it is disclosure from the *sod* of God. Second, it frames the chapter's entire logic: if God reveals before He acts, and the prophets have been told, then Israel has no excuse. Warning preceded disaster. God did not act without announcement. Verse 8 then draws the consequence with two parallel rhetorical questions: 'A lion has roared! Who will not fear? The Lord God has spoken! Who can but prophesy?' The prophet's compulsion is as irresistible as a community's instinctive terror at a lion's roar. This is Amos's implicit defense of his own ministry — he did not choose to prophesy against a nation that did not want to hear; he could not remain silent when God had roared."
